  "issue_number": 380,
  "issue_title": "[Bug]: Contributor outcome `totals` mix incompatible fallback sources, so `pullRequests \u2260 merged + open + closed` and `closedPullRequestRate` can exceed 1 for cache-only contributors",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nIn `buildContributorOutcomeHistory`, the per-repo outcomes are derived from one internally-consistent source and explicitly preserve `pullRequests \u2265 mergedPullRequests + openPullRequests + closedPullRequests`:\n\n```ts\n// src/signals/engine.ts:1479-1482  (per-repo \u2014 internally consistent)\nconst pullRequests = official?.pullRequests ?? Math.max(cachedPrs.length, cachedStat?.pullRequests ?? 0);\nconst mergedPullRequests = official?.mergedPullRequests ?? Math.max(cachedPrs.filter((pr) => pr.mergedAt || pr.state === \"merged\").length, cachedStat?.mergedPullRequests ?? 0);\nconst openPullRequests = official?.openPullRequests ?? Math.max(cachedPrs.filter((pr) => pr.state === \"open\").length, cachedStat?.openPullRequests ?? 0);\nconst closedPullRequests = official?.closedPullRequests ?? Math.max(cachedPrs.filter((pr) => pr.state === \"closed\" && !pr.mergedAt).length, pullRequests - mergedPullRequests - openPullRequests, 0);\n```\n\nBut the **totals** do not sum those consistent per-repo outcomes. When the official Gittensor snapshot is absent, each PR total falls back to a *different* source:\n\n```ts\n// src/signals/engine.ts:1539-1553\nconst totals = {\n  pullRequests:       args.profile.gittensor?.totals.pullRequests       ?? args.profile.registeredRepoActivity.pullRequests,        // source A\n  mergedPullRequests: args.profile.gittensor?.totals.mergedPullRequests ?? args.profile.registeredRepoActivity.mergedPullRequests,  // source A\n  openPullRequests:   args.profile.gittensor?.totals.openPullRequests   ?? args.repoStats.reduce((sum, stat) => sum + stat.openPullRequests, 0), // source B (unfiltered repoStats)\n  closedPullRequests: args.profile.gittensor?.totals.closedPullRequests ?? repoOutcomes.reduce((sum, outcome) => sum + outcome.closedPullRequests, 0), // source C\n  closedPullRequestRate: 0,\n  issues:             args.profile.registeredRepoActivity.issues, // source A \u2014 and NO official fallback at all\n  openIssues:         args.profile.gittensor?.totals.openIssues   ?? repoOutcomes.reduce((sum, outcome) => sum + outcome.openIssues, 0),    // source C\n  closedIssues:       args.profile.gittensor?.totals.closedIssues ?? repoOutcomes.reduce((sum, outcome) => sum + outcome.closedIssues, 0),  // source C\n  ...\n};\ntotals.closedPullRequestRate = rate(totals.closedPullRequests, totals.pullRequests);\n```\n\n`closedPullRequests`, `openIssues`, `closedIssues`, `solvedIssues`, and `validSolvedIssues` correctly fall back to summing the (login-scoped, internally-consistent) `repoOutcomes`. But `pullRequests` / `mergedPullRequests` fall back to `registeredRepoActivity` (a *separate* aggregate that itself uses `Math.max(authored, statSum)` per repo), `openPullRequests` falls back to a raw `repoStats` sum, and `issues` falls back to `registeredRepoActivity.issues` with **no** official fallback. Three (four) incompatible derivations for fields that must be consistent.\n\nTwo distinct defects fall out of this:\n\n1. **Broken invariant + out-of-range rate.** Because `pullRequests` (source A) is computed independently of `merged`/`open`/`closed` (sources A/B/C), `pullRequests \u2260 merged + open + closed`, and `closedPullRequestRate = rate(closedPullRequests, pullRequests)` (`:1553`) can exceed `1.0` (or otherwise misrepresent the real closed rate).\n2. **`openPullRequests` is not login-scoped.** Every other `repoStats` access in this function filters to the subject contributor \u2014 `args.repoStats.filter((stat) => sameLogin(stat.login, args.login))` (`engine.ts:1464`), the login-scoped `statsByRepo` (`:1470`), and the sibling reconciliation function (`:1591`/`:1596`). The `totals.openPullRequests` reduce (`:1542`) is the lone unfiltered `repoStats` sum, so any caller that passes a multi-login stat list sums other contributors' open PRs into this contributor's total.\n\n## Failure mode (concrete example)\n\nA contributor without an official Gittensor snapshot (the common case for new/unranked contributors \u2014 the same population as #317) has cached activity across repos giving `repoOutcomes` summing to `merged = 4`, `open = 7`, `closed = 5`, while `registeredRepoActivity.pullRequests = 10` (its own `Math.max` aggregate):\n\n- **Current:** `totals.pullRequests = 10` (source A), `merged = 4`, `open = 7`, `closed = 5` \u2192 `4 + 7 + 5 = 16 \u2260 10`, and `closedPullRequestRate = rate(5, 10) = 0.5` computed against a `pullRequests` denominator that disagrees with the parts. In skews where `closed > pullRequests`, the rate exceeds `1.0`.\n- **Correct (sum the consistent per-repo outcomes):** `pullRequests = 16`, `merged = 4`, `open = 7`, `closed = 5` \u2192 consistent, and `closedPullRequestRate = 5/16 \u2248 0.31`.\n\n## Downstream impact\n\n- `totals` is surfaced in the public outcome-history summary (`engine.ts:1568`), so the headline PR counts visibly don't add up for cache-only contributors.\n- `closedPullRequestRate` gates contributor strategy: `buildContributorStrategy` uses the `>= 0.35` closed-rate threshold for high-closure-risk / `avoidRepos` / readiness decisions (`engine.ts:2988`, `:3004`). A wrong or `>1` rate mis-classifies a contributor's risk.\n- `openPullRequests` feeds the open-PR-pressure signals; an unfiltered sum (defect 2) would inflate it with other contributors' work for any non-login-scoped caller.\n\n## Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Build a `ContributorProfile` with `source: \"github\"` and **no** `gittensor` snapshot, with cached PRs across repos such that `registeredRepoActivity.pullRequests` differs from the sum of per-repo merged/open/closed.\n2. Call `buildContributorOutcomeHistory(...)`.\n3. Observe `totals.pullRequests !== totals.mergedPullRequests + totals.openPullRequests + totals.closedPullRequests`, and a `closedPullRequestRate` computed against the inconsistent denominator.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nWhen official totals are absent, all PR/issue totals are derived from the same internally-consistent, login-scoped `repoOutcomes` (as `closedPullRequests`/`openIssues`/etc. already are), so `pullRequests = merged + open + closed`, `issues = openIssues + closedIssues`, `closedPullRequestRate \u2208 [0, 1]`, and the totals reflect only the subject contributor.\n\n## Actual behavior\n\n`pullRequests`/`mergedPullRequests` fall back to `registeredRepoActivity`, `openPullRequests` to an unfiltered `repoStats` sum, and `issues` to `registeredRepoActivity.issues` with no official fallback \u2014 so the totals are internally inconsistent and `openPullRequests` is not login-scoped.\n\n## Suggested fix\n\n- Derive the cache fallback for `pullRequests`, `mergedPullRequests`, `openPullRequests`, and `issues` by summing the already-computed `repoOutcomes` (login-scoped and internally consistent), matching how `closedPullRequests` / `openIssues` / `closedIssues` / `solvedIssues` already fall back. Concretely, a small helper `const sumOutcomes = (key) => repoOutcomes.reduce((sum, outcome) => sum + outcome[key], 0)` used for all PR/issue totals, and compute `issues` as `openIssues + closedIssues`. This fixes both the invariant/rate defect and the login-scoping of `openPullRequests`.\n- Add fail-on-revert coverage: a cache-only contributor (no official snapshot) yields `totals.pullRequests === merged + open + closed`, `totals.issues === openIssues + closedIssues`, and `closedPullRequestRate <= 1`; and `openPullRequests` ignores another login's `repoStats` rows.",
